f the judicial elections literature, and presents new evidence on a wide range of important topics, including: the history of judicial elections; an understanding of the types of judicial elections; electoral competition during races; the increasing importance of campaign financing; voting in judicial elections; the role interest groups play in supporting candidates; party organizing in supposedly non-partisan elections; judicial accountability; media coverage; and judicial reform of elections.Running for Judge is an engaging, accessible, empirical analysis of the major issues surrounding judicial elections, with contributions from prominent scholars in the fields of judicial politics, political behavior, and law.Contributors: Lawrence Baum, Chris W. Bonneau, Brent D. Boyea, Paul Brace, Rachel P. Caufield, Jennifer Segal Diascro, Brian Frederick, Deborah Goldberg, Melinda Gann Hall, Richard L. Hasen, David Klein, Brian F. Schaffner, and Matthew J. Streb.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aJudgeszUnited StatesxStatesxElection. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh  aJudge.  aRunning.  aaccessible.  aanalysis.  abehavior.  acontributions.  aelections.  aempirical.  aengaging.  afields.  afrom.  aissues.  ajudicial.  alaw.  amajor.  apolitical.  apolitics.  aprominent.  ascholars.  asurrounding.  awith.1 aBaum, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonneau, Chris W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyea, Brent D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrace, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaufield, Rachel P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrederick, Brian, 